! conclusion: Standing in the Circle
+ context: You are helping a doctoral researcher shift from student to colleague inside a research team.
+ if: Doctoral researchers are expected to participate in research teams, represent their work, and contribute to shared decisions, yet their reasoning and trade-offs remain invisible to peers.
+ however: When a researcher is always positioned as ‚Äúlearner receiving instruction,‚Äù collaborators miss the moment when they are ready to act as colleagues.
+ then: Provide structured opportunities for them to narrate decisions in a peer-facing format‚Äîdecision notes, reflective summaries, short presentations of provisional conclusions‚Äîso their judgement is legible to the team rather than hidden inside supervisory conversations.
+ because: Explicit reasoning creates recognition: supervisors and peers can respond at the appropriate level, collaboration becomes more mature, and the researcher internalises professional discourse norms that move them from student to colleague.
+ next-steps:
+   next[Ask them to produce a decision note after the next team meeting.]
+   next[Schedule a short peer-facing update where they present one provisional conclusion.]
